AI Pipelines
AI Model Support on Livepeer
Full compatibility matrix for AI model families on Livepeer via ComfyUI. Which models run, which are conditional, and which are incompatible - with reasons.

What models can run on Livepeer, and which are better suited?
This page lists all known model families commonly used via ComfyUI, with compatibility ratings for Livepeer’s real-time, GPU-worker constraints. Nothing here implies that a listed model is officially supported or pre-loaded on the network - it reflects whether a model’s execution shape fits Livepeer well.
​
Legend
✓ Likely runnable - fits real-time / GPU-worker constraints
⚠ Conditional - depends on latency, VRAM, orchestration, or batching
✗ Not suitable - design mismatch: stateful, CPU-bound, or non-deterministic
​
1. Diffusion Models (Image / Video)
​
Stable Diffusion family
Model	Fit	Notes
Stable Diffusion 1.4 / 1.5 / 2.0 / 2.1	✓	Foundation of most ComfyUI workflows, including frame-by-frame video processing.
SDXL (Base / Refiner / Turbo)	⚠	VRAM + latency. Higher-capacity SD variant; Turbo trades quality for speed.
SD-Turbo / LCM / Lightning	✓	Accelerated diffusion converging in very few steps - ideal for low-latency generation.
Kandinsky	⚠	Less optimised, heavier. Semantic understanding focus.
DeepFloyd IF	✗	Multi-stage, extreme VRAM. Cascaded pipeline with large frozen text encoders.
Why blocked (DeepFloyd): VRAM pressure, multi-stage graphs, inference latency.
​
Video diffusion models
Model	Fit	Notes
StreamDiffusion	✓	Real-time architecture that reuses latent states across frames - purpose-built for live video.
Stable Video Diffusion (SVD)	⚠	Latency + frame buffering. Temporal consistency model for short clips.
AnimateDiff	⚠	Temporal batching required. Adds motion modules to SD for animated sequences.
VideoCrafter	✗	Offline batch generation only. Not designed for interactive use.
Wan / Wan 2.x	⚠	VRAM heavy; real-time guarantees unclear. Emerging world-style video diffusion.
Gen-2–style world models	✗	Stateful, non-deterministic. Maintains long-term scene memory - incompatible.
Why blocked (batch video): temporal state, batch-only execution, non-real-time.
​
2. Control & Conditioning Models
​
ControlNet
Model	Fit	Notes
Canny	✓	Edge-detection conditioning. Guides diffusion using detected outlines.
Depth	✓	Depth map conditioning for structure and spatial consistency.
OpenPose	✓	Human body, hand, and facial keypoints from images or video.
Normal / Lineart / Scribble	✓	Structural ControlNets using surface normals, line drawings, or sketches.
Tile / Inpaint	⚠	Memory intensive. Tiled generation or region-specific editing for large images.
Multi-ControlNet compositions	⚠	GPU saturation risk. Multiple simultaneous ControlNets enforcing several constraints.
​
T2I / I2I Adapters
Model	Fit	Notes
IP-Adapter	✓	Image-based style or identity guidance without retraining.
Reference-only adapters	✓	Lightweight; biases generation toward a reference image.
Style adapters	✓	Transfers artistic or visual style.
​
3. Encoders, VAEs, and Latents
Model	Fit	Notes
SD VAEs	✓	Standard VAEs for encoding/decoding images to/from latent space.
Custom / fine-tuned VAEs	⚠	Memory intensive but often worth it for quality improvement.
Latent consistency decoders	✓	Optimised for fewer diffusion steps and faster convergence.
​
4. Vision Models (Non-Diffusion)
​
Detection / Segmentation
Model	Fit	Notes
YOLO (v5–v8)	⚠	CPU/GPU mix. Real-time object detection; latency varies by GPU availability.
SAM / SAM2	⚠	VRAM + latency. Pixel-level mask generation - works but heavy.
GroundingDINO	⚠	Vision–language detection linking text prompts to detected objects.
Detectron2	✗	CPU-heavy, batch-oriented. Research framework not suited to real-time.
​
Depth / Geometry
Model	Fit	Notes
MiDaS	✓	Monocular depth estimation from a single image. Fast and reliable.
DepthAnything	✓	High-quality depth estimation optimised for speed and accuracy.
ZoeDepth	⚠	Higher precision at increased compute cost.
​
5. Face, Pose & Human Models
Model	Fit	Notes
OpenPose	✓	Body, hand, and face keypoint extraction - well-suited for live video.
DensePose	⚠	Heavy. Maps pixels to 3D body surface representation.
Face parsing	⚠	Segments facial regions (eyes, mouth, hair, skin).
FaceSwap / ReFace models	✗	Legal + state constraints. Identity replacement raises compliance issues.
First Order Motion Model	✗	Temporal state. Motion transfer from driving video to source subject.
​
6. Audio & Music Models
Model	Fit	Notes
Audio diffusion (Riffusion-style)	⚠	Conditional. Generates audio via diffusion - marginal real-time fit.
MusicGen	✗	Long-running, batch. Text-to-music generation for full clips.
Bark / TTS models	✗	Stateful, streaming mismatch. Long context windows.
Why blocked: long context windows, non-frame-based execution.
For real-time audio workloads (live ASR, live translation, streaming transcription), see Workload Fit → ASR pipeline examples. These use Whisper or similar and are excellent fits.
​
7. Multimodal & VLMs
Model	Fit	Notes
CLIP	✓	Joint image–text embedding for scoring, ranking, and guidance.
BLIP / BLIP-2	⚠	Vision–language for captioning and visual Q&A - conditional on latency.
LLaVA	✗	LLM state + latency. Combines vision encoders with large LLMs.
Qwen-VL	✗	Vision–language with LLM reasoning - orchestration mismatch.
​
8. LLMs (Text-Centric)
Model	Fit	Notes
LLaMA / Mistral / Qwen	✗	Autoregressive text generation; token streaming + memory residency incompatible.
GPT-style decoders	✗	Token-by-token state - fundamental orchestration mismatch.
Why blocked: token streaming, memory residency, orchestration mismatch.
​
9. 3D / NeRF / World Models
Model	Fit	Notes
NeRF	✗	Offline training. 3D scene reconstruction from images - multi-hour jobs.
Gaussian Splatting	✗	Stateful scenes. Learned Gaussian primitives for 3D rendering.
DreamFusion	✗	Multi-hour optimisation jobs. Not real-time compatible.
​
10. Utility / Pre/Post Models
Model	Fit	Notes
ESRGAN / Real-ESRGAN	⚠	Image super-resolution. Works but VRAM-intensive for large inputs.
GFPGAN	⚠	Face restoration. Enhances facial detail in low-quality images.
Background removal (U2Net)	⚠	Salient object detection for background isolation. Conditional on throughput.
​
Core takeaway
ComfyUI can orchestrate almost any PyTorch model. But:
Livepeer favours stateless, frame-based, deterministic inference
Long-running, stateful, or batch-only models are fundamentally incompatible
Real-time video imposes hard physics limits, not software ones
This matrix is intentionally conservative. If your model doesn’t appear here, apply the Workload Fit decision tree to evaluate it.